  "text": "## MVCC Compaction Implementation in etcd\n\n### 1. Compaction Schedule: Periodic vs Revision-Based\n\nThe compaction scheduling is implemented through two strategies in `server/etcdserver/api/v3compactor/`:\n\n**Periodic Compaction** (`periodic.go`):\n- The `Periodic` struct implements time-based compaction with a configurable retention period\n- The `Run()` method starts a goroutine that records revisions at regular intervals (every 1/10th of the period)\n- Keeps a sliding window of revisions and compacts the oldest one once the retention period elapses\n- Supports different periods: for periods >1 hour, it compacts every hour; otherwise, it compacts every period interval\n- Implements Pause/Resume functionality for graceful shutdown\n\n**Revision-Based Compaction** (`revision.go`):\n- The `Revision` struct maintains a fixed number of revisions as history\n- Compacts every 5 minutes, removing revisions older than the specified retention count from the current revision\n- Simpler strategy than periodic: keeps only N revisions in history\n\nBoth strategies are instantiated via the factory function in `compactor.go` using the `New()` function which supports `ModePeriodic` and `ModeRevision` modes.\n\n### 2. Compaction of Revision Indices\n\nRevision index compaction happens at multiple levels:\n\n**Store-Level Compaction** (`kvstore.go`):\n- `Compact(trace, rev)` is the main entry point that accepts a trace and revision number\n- `updateCompactRev(rev)` updates and persists the compaction revision in the backend storage\n- `checkPrevCompactionCompleted()` checks if the previous compaction finished before starting a new one\n- Uses FIFO scheduler to run compaction as a background job\n- Stores the compaction state using `SetScheduledCompact` and `UnsafeSetFinishedCompact` in the Meta bucket\n\n**Batch-Level Compaction** (`kvstore_compaction.go`):\n- `scheduleCompaction(compactMainRev, prevCompactRev)` iterates through key-value pairs in batches\n- Deletes keys that are not in the \"keep\" map (keys that have revisions older than the compaction point)\n- Processes in configurable batches (default 1000) with sleep intervals to avoid blocking\n- Computes a hash of the compacted data for consistency verification\n- Stores metrics about compaction duration, number of keys compacted, and database size\n\n**Key Index Compaction** (`key_index.go`):\n- `compact(atRev, available)` removes versions of keys with revisions <= atRev except the largest one\n- Removes generations that become empty during compaction\n- `keep(atRev, available)` identifies which revisions must be preserved (called by the store)\n- `doCompact()` walks through generations to find the first revision <= atRev\n- Maintains an \"available\" map that tracks which revisions need to be kept\n\n**Index Interface** (`index.go`):\n- The `index` interface provides `Compact(rev)` and `Keep(rev)` methods\n- `treeIndex` implements this interface using a B-tree of `keyIndex` objects\n\n### 3. Notification of Watch Streams Spanning Compacted Revisions\n\nWatch streams are notified when they span a compacted revision through the `watcher_group.go` implementation:\n\n**Watcher Group Compaction Detection** (`watcher_group.go`):\n- `choose(maxWatchers, curRev, compactRev)` selects watchers to sync and checks for compacted ones\n- `chooseAll(curRev, compactRev)` iterates through all watchers and identifies those with `minRev < compactRev`\n- When a compacted watcher is detected (line 251-259), it sends a `WatchResponse` with `CompactRevision` field set\n- Marks the watcher as compacted with `w.compacted = true` and removes it from the watcher group\n- If the watcher channel is full, it retries next time during the next sync cycle\n\n**Watch Stream Notification** (`watchable_store.go`):\n- `syncWatchers()` is called every 100ms by `syncWatchersLoop()` to synchronize unsynced watchers\n- Calls `watcher_group.choose()` which handles the compaction notification\n- Unsynced watchers are stored in the `unsynced` watcher group\n- When a watcher's minRev falls below the compaction revision, it receives a compacted notification\n\n**Watch Response Types** (`watcher.go`):\n- `WatchResponse` struct has a `CompactRevision` field that is set when a watcher is cancelled due to compaction\n- The client receives this response and knows to reconnect with a newer starting revision\n\n### 4. Slow Watch Detection\n\nSlow watch detection identifies watchers that cannot keep up with the watch stream:\n\n**Victim Watcher Handling** (`watchable_store.go`):\n- When a watcher's channel is full and `send()` returns false, the watcher is marked as a \"victim\"\n- Victims are moved to the `victims` batch (line 390-395, 505)\n- `moveVictims()` runs in a separate loop (`syncVictimsLoop()`) to periodically retry sending to victims\n- Victims are processed every 10ms, attempting to drain the backlog of events\n- Once a victim successfully receives its events, it transitions back to synced or unsynced state\n\n**Unsynced Watcher Tracking** (`watchable_store.go`):\n- When a new watch starts with `startRev <= currentRev`, it's marked as unsynced (line 140)\n- Unsynced watchers are added to the `unsynced` watcher group (line 149)\n- The `slowWatcherGauge` metric tracks the count of unsynced watchers (line 148)\n- The `syncWatchersLoop()` processes up to `maxWatchersPerSync` (512) unsynced watchers every 100ms\n\n**Metrics** (`metrics.go`):\n- `slowWatcherGauge` (Prometheus Gauge) tracks \"Total number of unsynced slow watchers\"\n- Updated in `syncWatchers()` (line 411): counts both unsynced watchers and victims\n- Incremented in `watch()` when a watcher starts as unsynced (line 148)\n- Decremented when watchers are moved to synced or cancelled (line 164, 191, 324)\n\n**Watch State Transitions**:\n- Synced watchers that fall behind become unsynced\n- Unsynced watchers with full channels become victims\n- Victims are retried until successful, then transition back to synced/unsynced\n- Slow watchers that span compacted revisions receive CompactRevision and are removed\n\nThis architecture ensures reliable delivery of watch events even under high load, with backpressure handling through victim batches and periodic retry mechanisms."
